{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"173"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/173"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.12,0.57,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"173"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107573"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/173"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"173"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90024"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"101"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42015"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107573"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of light-headedness and progressively worsening shortness of breath. He has also experienced several episodes of dull chest discomfort that occur when walking to the bus stop that last five to 10 minutes. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. Cardiovascular examination reveals a harsh ejection systolic murmur that radiates to the carotid arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional physical signs would most likely be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malar flush","Murmur radiating to the axilla","Raised jugular venous pressure","Narrow pulse pressure","Loud second heart sound"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of aortic stenosis: angina, dyspnoea, and presyncope. The ejection systolic murmur radiating to the carotids is characteristic of aortic stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENarrow pulse pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely additional finding. In aortic stenosis, reduced stroke volume leads to decreased systolic pressure while diastolic pressure remains relatively unchanged, resulting in a narrowed pulse pressure (the difference between systolic and diastolic blood pressure).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalar flush\u003C/strong\u003E is classically associated with mitral stenosis, occurring due to low cardiac output and pulmonary hypertension leading to hypoxemia and cutaneous vasodilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMurmur radiating to the axilla\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of mitral regurgitation and mitral valve prolapse. While aortic stenosis murmurs can radiate to the axilla (Gallavardin phenomenon), this is not the most specific finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaised jugular venous pressure\u003C/strong\u003E indicates increased right atrial pressure. While this may occur in end-stage aortic stenosis when left heart failure progresses to right heart failure, it is not a characteristic early finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoud second heart sound\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely, as the intensity of S2 typically decreases with worsening aortic stenosis due to reduced mobility of the calcified valve leaflets. In severe cases, S2 may become inaudible.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aortic stenosis classically presents with angina, dyspnoea, and presyncope/syncope.","A narrow pulse pressure is characteristic of aortic stenosis due to reduced stroke volume.","The intensity of S2 typically decreases as aortic stenosis becomes more severe due to reduced valve mobility."],"references":["Lilly L. Pathophysiology of Heart Disease. Sixth Edition. Boston: Wolters Kluwer; 2016.","Dennis M, Bowen W, Cho L. Mechanisms of Clinical Signs. First Edition. Chatswood, NWS: Elsevier; 2012:181.","Rahman A, Rowe M. Aortic stenosis: Update in monitoring and management. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2024;53:444-8. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/july/aortic-stenosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90024"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"173"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90024"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T09:36:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T09:36:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"173"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107573"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"t